[...]

Schlippenbach, for his part, takes a particularly oblique approach to harmony,
with dense clusters and irregular intervals tending to crowd out the more open
and resonant moments. As both a player and a composer, he adopts an
architectural approach to sound. Three improvisers, playing as intensely and
interactively as they possibly can, are barely enough to assemble the craggy
structures that emerge here. So in some sense Pakistani Pomade is both a
reflection of open possibilities and concerted effort.

